values
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:86f9797e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which technique means working out the step-by-step sequence of instructions needed to solve a problem?", "options": ["Algorithmic thinking", "Decomposition, because it always breaks the problem into an ordered list of numbered instructions to follow", "Abstraction", "Testing, since it always finds every single step required to solve the whole problem correctly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Algorithmic thinking is working out the ordered steps (the logic) needed to solve a problem."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:d7f3b480', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which technique means removing or hiding detail that is not needed to solve a problem?", "options": ["Abstraction", "Decomposition, because it removes every unnecessary sub-problem until only one single detail about the task is left", "Algorithmic thinking", "Refinement"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Abstraction removes or hides unneeded detail so only what matters is kept."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:db885bdf', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A programmer chooses to store only a customer''s name and order number, and leaves out their exact home address. Which technique is this?", "options": ["Abstraction — irrelevant detail has been left out because it is not needed", "Decomposition — the customer record has been split into two entirely separate smaller programs that must be built one after another", "Algorithmic thinking — the steps needed to look up a customer have been listed", "Testing — the programmer is checking that the data is stored correctly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Leaving out unneeded detail (the address) is abstraction, not decomposition, algorithmic thinking or testing."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:02b9c4cb', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A large ''build a school website'' problem is split into ''homepage'', ''staff pages'' and ''contact form''. Which technique is this?", "options": ["Decomposition — the overall problem has been broken into smaller, more manageable sub-problems", "Abstraction, because every website has to have unnecessary detail removed before any of its pages can possibly be built at all", "Algorithmic thinking — the exact steps for building the whole website have been written out", "An algorithm, which is the finished set of instructions that solves a problem"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Splitting an overall problem into separate parts (homepage, staff pages, contact form) is decomposition."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:d2a8f896', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A student writes out, in order: ''ask for two numbers, add them together, then display the result.'' Which technique is this?", "options": ["Algorithmic thinking — the ordered steps needed to solve the problem have been worked out", "Decomposition, because the single task of adding two numbers has somehow been split into several completely separate sub-problems", "Abstraction — unnecessary detail about the two numbers has been removed", "Debugging — mistakes in a finished program are being found and corrected"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Writing out an ordered sequence of steps (ask, add, display) is algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:d201b74a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is an algorithm?", "options": ["A finished set of step-by-step instructions that solves a problem", "A thinking skill used to remove unnecessary detail from a large and complicated real-world problem before it is solved", "A named store in memory whose value can change while a program runs", "A simplified diagram that shows only the roads in a particular area"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An algorithm is the finished, ordered set of instructions produced by algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:cddf598c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is the best definition of ''define a problem'' in computational thinking?", "options": ["Working out exactly what a problem involves before trying to solve it", "Writing the final working program code in a specific programming language such as Python or Java", "Testing a finished solution to check that it produces the correct result every time", "Removing every single feature of a problem so that literally nothing about it remains to be solved"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Defining a problem means working out exactly what it involves before attempting a solution."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:72186279', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why might a programmer decompose a sub-problem even further, into smaller sub-problems?", "options": ["Because the sub-problem is still too complex to solve or understand as a single piece", "Because computational thinking rules require exactly three levels of decomposition for absolutely every problem, with no exceptions", "Because abstraction can only be used once on any given problem, no matter how complicated it is", "Because algorithms are not allowed to contain more than one single step in total"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A sub-problem can be decomposed again if it is still too complex to tackle directly — there is no fixed number of levels."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:mcq:58f47e2c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A programmer is planning a solution and works out the order: ''check stock is available, THEN take payment, THEN confirm the order.'' What has the programmer produced?", "options": ["An algorithm — the ordered steps needed to solve the problem", "A model, which is a simplified representation of something real created using only abstraction and nothing else", "A sub-problem, which is one smaller part of a larger overall problem", "A decomposition diagram that shows every possible detail about the order in full"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An ordered sequence of steps that solves a problem is an algorithm — the result of algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:0fa0afec', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Abstraction means adding more detail to a problem so that it becomes more accurate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Abstraction means the opposite — removing or hiding unnecessary detail so that only the parts that matter are kept."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:f7121545', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Decomposition means breaking a large problem into smaller, more manageable sub-problems."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — that is exactly what decomposition means."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:54d27c40', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Algorithmic thinking is the process of writing the final program code in a specific language such as Python."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Algorithmic thinking is working out the step-by-step logic needed to solve a problem — writing it in a specific language comes afterwards."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:3cfcefcc', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A road map is an example of abstraction, because it leaves out details that are not needed, such as the exact height of every building."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a map keeps the roads (what''s needed for a journey) and hides irrelevant detail."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:9bc3ea8e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Decomposition can be applied more than once, breaking a sub-problem down into even smaller sub-problems."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — if a sub-problem is still too complex, it can be decomposed again."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:5ca8fb38', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Computational thinking is only used by professional programmers once they have already started writing code."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Computational thinking is used to plan a solution BEFORE any code is written, and can be applied to any complex problem, not just programming."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:9fd9e068', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Breaking a big problem into smaller sub-problems can make it possible to share the work between several people."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — separate sub-problems can be divided between different people in a team."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tf:4855e77c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Algorithmic thinking must always be applied before decomposition, in every case."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Usually decomposition happens first, splitting the problem into sub-problems; algorithmic thinking is then applied to work out the steps for each sub-problem."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:2a69a2bc', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is computational thinking?", "reading": "<h4>Working out how to solve a problem before you code it</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Computational thinking</strong> is a set of thinking skills used to work out how to solve a problem — <strong>before</strong> any program code is written.</li>\n<li>It uses three main techniques: <strong>abstraction</strong> (removing unnecessary detail), <strong>decomposition</strong> (breaking a problem into smaller parts) and <strong>algorithmic thinking</strong> (working out the steps needed).</li>\n<li>Together, these techniques help a programmer <strong>define</strong> a problem (work out exactly what it involves) and <strong>refine</strong> it (simplify it), so that it becomes easier to solve.</li>\n<li>Computational thinking is not only used by programmers — it is a general way of tackling any large or complex problem, on a computer or off one.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which of the following best describes computational thinking?", "options": ["A set of thinking skills used to work out how to solve a problem, applied before any program code is written", "A programming language used to write the final version of a solution once every step has already been planned out", "A single technique for removing unnecessary detail from a problem", "The process of testing a finished program to find and fix any bugs"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Computational thinking is the set of thinking skills (abstraction, decomposition, algorithmic thinking) used to plan a solution before any code is written."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:2f1fed91', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Abstraction", "reading": "<h4>Removing or hiding unnecessary detail</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Abstraction</strong> means removing or hiding the detail that is <strong>not needed</strong> to solve a problem, so that only the parts that matter are left.</li>\n<li>A road map is a classic example: it shows the roads you need for a journey, but leaves out every building, tree and fence along the way. Those details are real, but they are <strong>not relevant</strong> to finding a route.</li>\n<li>A <strong>model</strong> of something (a diagram, a plan, a set of program data) is a simplified version created using abstraction — it keeps the features that matter for the task and ignores the rest.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does abstraction mean in computational thinking?", "options": ["Removing or hiding unnecessary detail so that only the parts of a problem that matter are kept", "Adding as much extra detail as possible so that every single feature of a real situation is represented", "Breaking a large problem down into smaller, more manageable sub-problems", "Working out the exact order of steps needed to solve a problem"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Abstraction means removing or hiding unneeded detail. Adding more detail is the opposite of abstraction; splitting into parts is decomposition; working out steps is algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:d1c837f6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Abstraction in practice", "reading": "<h4>Deciding what to keep and what to leave out</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Abstraction is a <strong>choice</strong>: for any real problem there are far more details than a program (or a person) actually needs.</li>\n<li>Example: a school''s student record system needs a student''s <strong>name, ID number and year group</strong> — but it does not need their shoe size or favourite colour. Leaving those out is abstraction.</li>\n<li>Example: a bus tracking app shows <strong>which stop a bus is near and when it will arrive</strong> — the driver''s exact GPS coordinates and engine data are hidden from the passenger, because they add nothing useful.</li>\n<li>Good abstraction keeps a problem <strong>simple enough to work with</strong>, without losing anything that is actually needed.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A programmer designing a school library system decides to store each book''s title, author and shelf number, but not the exact minute it was printed. What is this an example of?", "options": ["Abstraction — irrelevant detail (the exact printing time) is left out because it is not needed to find a book", "Decomposition — the library system has been broken down into smaller, separate parts that can be solved one at a time", "Algorithmic thinking — the steps needed to search for a book have been listed", "An error, because a complete system must always store every single piece of data that could possibly exist"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Leaving out detail that isn''t needed (the printing time) so that only the useful fields remain is abstraction, not decomposition or algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:8d0dd8a1', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Decomposition", "reading": "<h4>Breaking a big problem into smaller pieces</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Decomposition</strong> means breaking a large, complex problem down into <strong>smaller, more manageable sub-problems</strong> that can be tackled one at a time.</li>\n<li>Example: building a quiz app is a big problem. Decomposed, it becomes several smaller ones: \"show a question\", \"check the answer\", \"keep score\", \"show the final result\".</li>\n<li>If a sub-problem is still too complex, it can be <strong>decomposed again</strong> into even smaller sub-problems, until each one is simple enough to solve directly.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does decomposition mean?", "options": ["Breaking a large, complex problem down into smaller, more manageable sub-problems", "Removing or hiding every possible piece of detail so that literally nothing about the original problem is left to consider", "Working out the step-by-step sequence of instructions needed to solve a problem", "Testing every sub-problem at the very end, once the whole program has already been completed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Decomposition splits a large problem into smaller sub-problems. Removing detail is abstraction; working out steps is algorithmic thinking."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:d56bc0b6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Decomposition in practice", "reading": "<h4>Why smaller pieces are easier to solve</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Each sub-problem can be <strong>looked at, solved and tested on its own</strong>, without having to think about the whole problem at the same time.</li>\n<li>Different sub-problems can sometimes be <strong>shared out between different people</strong> in a team, so several parts can be worked on at once.</li>\n<li>A solution to one sub-problem can sometimes be <strong>reused</strong> elsewhere — for example, a \"check the answer\" sub-problem from a quiz app could be reused in a different quiz.</li>\n<li>Decomposition does not solve the problem by itself — it just makes the problem <strong>easier to plan and to solve</strong>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A team of three programmers is building a booking system. They agree that one person will build the login screen, one will build the search screen, and one will build the payment screen. What allowed them to split the work like this?", "options": ["Decomposition — the overall problem had already been broken down into separate, more manageable sub-problems", "Abstraction — every unnecessary detail about the booking system had been removed before any work started at all", "Algorithmic thinking — the exact order of steps for the whole system had been written out for everyone to follow", "A coincidence, since a booking system cannot actually be split into separate parts by different programmers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Splitting an overall problem into separate parts that different people can work on is decomposition."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:96736d73', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Algorithmic thinking", "reading": "<h4>Working out the steps to follow</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Algorithmic thinking</strong> means working out the <strong>step-by-step sequence of instructions</strong> — the logic — needed to solve a problem, or a sub-problem.</li>\n<li>It is usually applied <strong>after</strong> a problem has been decomposed, one sub-problem at a time: for each sub-problem, work out exactly what steps need to happen, and in what order.</li>\n<li>The finished sequence of steps is called an <strong>algorithm</strong>. It can be written in plain English, as a diagram, or later turned into program code.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does algorithmic thinking mean?", "options": ["Working out the step-by-step sequence of instructions needed to solve a problem", "Removing detail from a problem so that only the features which are actually needed for a solution are kept", "Breaking a problem down into smaller sub-problems that can be solved one at a time", "Running a finished program many times to check that it produces the correct result"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Algorithmic thinking is working out the ordered steps (the logic) needed to solve a problem. The other options describe abstraction, decomposition and testing."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:e9b10014', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Algorithmic thinking in practice", "reading": "<h4>From steps to a working algorithm</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Take the sub-problem \"check whether a number is a valid exam mark (0 to 100)\". Algorithmic thinking works out the steps: <em>ask for the number → check it is 0 or more → check it is 100 or less → if both are true, accept it, otherwise reject it</em>.</li>\n<li>Writing the steps out clearly, in the right order, <strong>before</strong> touching a keyboard makes it far easier to spot mistakes in the logic — and far easier to translate into any programming language afterwards.</li>\n<li>A good algorithm is <strong>precise</strong> (each step has one clear meaning) and <strong>complete</strong> (it covers every case the problem needs, not just the obvious one).</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why is it useful to work out the steps of an algorithm before writing any program code?", "options": ["It makes it easier to spot mistakes in the logic first, and easier to turn the steps into code in any language afterwards", "It is not useful at all, because a programmer should always start by typing code directly into an editor without planning anything out in advance first", "It removes the need to ever test the program once it has finally been written and completed", "It automatically translates the steps into working code without a programmer needing to type anything"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Planning the steps first makes mistakes easier to spot and the algorithm easier to turn into code afterwards — it does not remove the need for testing or write the code for you."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:26858413', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Defining and refining a problem", "reading": "<h4>Using all three techniques together</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The three techniques are not used in strict isolation — they work together to help a programmer <strong>define</strong> a problem (work out exactly what it involves) and <strong>refine</strong> it (make it simpler and clearer) before any code is written.</li>\n<li>A typical order: use <strong>abstraction</strong> to strip away detail that does not matter, use <strong>decomposition</strong> to split what is left into sub-problems, then use <strong>algorithmic thinking</strong> to work out the steps needed for each sub-problem.</li>\n<li>This does not have to be a one-way process — a programmer might return to an earlier technique if a sub-problem still turns out to be too complex, and decompose it further.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which of these best describes how abstraction, decomposition and algorithmic thinking are normally used together?", "options": ["Abstraction removes unneeded detail, decomposition splits what is left into sub-problems, and algorithmic thinking works out the steps for each sub-problem", "They must always be used in exactly the reverse order every single time, starting with algorithmic thinking, then decomposition, and only finally using abstraction at the very end", "Only one of the three techniques is ever needed to solve any given problem, so a programmer simply picks whichever one they prefer", "They are three completely unrelated skills that are never used on the same problem at the same time"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The three techniques normally work together in this order: abstraction removes detail, decomposition splits what''s left into parts, and algorithmic thinking works out each part''s steps."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:25553f5c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why computational thinking makes problems easier to solve", "reading": "<h4>The benefits of thinking before coding</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Simpler problems</strong> — a huge, complicated problem is hard to hold in your head all at once; abstraction and decomposition turn it into small pieces that are easy to understand.</li>\n<li><strong>Easier to test</strong> — each small sub-problem can be checked on its own, so mistakes are easier to find and fix than in one giant block of logic.</li>\n<li><strong>Easier to share out</strong> — separate sub-problems can be divided between different people, so a team can work on a problem at the same time.</li>\n<li><strong>Reusable solutions</strong> — a well-defined sub-problem, and the algorithm that solves it, can sometimes be reused in a different program.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which of these is a genuine benefit of using decomposition on a large problem?", "options": ["Each sub-problem is small enough to be solved, tested and understood on its own", "The overall problem magically disappears completely, so that no further work of any kind is ever required from anyone", "It guarantees that the final program will never contain a single bug or mistake of any kind whatsoever", "It means every sub-problem must always be solved by exactly one single programmer working entirely alone"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Decomposition makes each sub-problem small enough to solve, test and understand on its own — it does not remove the problem, guarantee no bugs, or force one programmer to work alone."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:learn:05281237', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Spotting the right technique in a scenario", "reading": "<h4>How to tell abstraction, decomposition and algorithmic thinking apart</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Exam scenarios describe someone solving a problem and ask which technique is being used. Look for these cues:</li>\n<li><strong>Abstraction</strong> — the scenario talks about <em>leaving out, ignoring, hiding or simplifying</em> detail that isn''t needed.</li>\n<li><strong>Decomposition</strong> — the scenario talks about <em>splitting, dividing or breaking the problem into separate parts</em> or stages.</li>\n<li><strong>Algorithmic thinking</strong> — the scenario talks about working out the <em>order of steps</em>, or planning what happens <em>first, next and last</em>.</li>\n<li>Answer using the exact term the mark scheme expects (e.g. \"decomposition\", not just \"breaking it up\") and, where asked, explain your choice using detail from the scenario.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A scenario says a student ''listed the exact order in which the robot should turn, move forward, and stop.'' Which technique does this describe?", "options": ["Algorithmic thinking — the student worked out the ordered sequence of steps the robot must follow", "Abstraction — the student removed every unnecessary detail about the robot before listing anything at all", "Decomposition — the student split the robot''s overall task into several completely separate, smaller sub-problems", "None of these — listing steps in order is not part of computational thinking in any way"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Listing an ordered sequence of steps (turn, move, stop) is algorithmic thinking — working out the logic to follow, not removing detail or splitting into sub-problems."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:f413d74a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking abstraction means adding more detail to a problem, to make it more accurate.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Abstraction means the opposite — it means <strong>removing or hiding</strong> detail that is not needed, so that only the parts of a problem that matter are left.</p>", "question": "Which of these correctly describes abstraction?", "options": ["Removing or hiding detail that is not needed, so only the important parts of a problem remain", "Adding as much extra detail as possible so that a problem is represented completely and perfectly, with nothing left out at all", "Splitting a problem into smaller, more manageable sub-problems", "Working out the order of steps needed to solve a problem"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Abstraction removes or hides unneeded detail — it does not add detail, split a problem into parts, or work out steps."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:ad905f69', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking decomposition and algorithmic thinking are the same thing.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> They are different: <strong>decomposition</strong> splits a problem into smaller <em>sub-problems</em>; <strong>algorithmic thinking</strong> works out the <em>steps</em> needed to solve a problem (or sub-problem).</p>", "question": "What is the difference between decomposition and algorithmic thinking?", "options": ["Decomposition splits a problem into sub-problems; algorithmic thinking works out the steps to solve a problem", "There is no real difference at all — the two terms are simply two completely different names that programmers use for exactly the same single technique", "Decomposition removes unnecessary detail; algorithmic thinking splits a problem into smaller parts", "Algorithmic thinking is only used once a program has already been completely finished and tested"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Decomposition splits a problem into sub-problems; algorithmic thinking works out the ordered steps needed to solve it. They are different techniques."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:d6389955', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing decomposition can only ever be applied once to a problem.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A sub-problem can be <strong>decomposed again</strong> if it is still too complex — decomposition can be applied more than once, breaking a problem down as many times as needed.</p>", "question": "A sub-problem is still too complicated to solve directly. What should a programmer do?", "options": ["Decompose the sub-problem again, breaking it into even smaller sub-problems", "Give up on decomposition completely, since it is only ever allowed to be used a single time on any one problem", "Apply abstraction instead, because decomposition cannot be used more than once under any circumstances", "Write the final program code immediately, without doing any further planning"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Decomposition can be applied more than once — a sub-problem that is still too complex can be broken down further."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:6d32f09f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing computational thinking is only relevant once you are already writing code.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Computational thinking is used <strong>before</strong> code is written, to plan and simplify a solution — and it applies to solving <em>any</em> complex problem, not only programming ones.</p>", "question": "When is computational thinking used?", "options": ["Before any code is written, to plan and simplify a solution to a problem", "Only after a program has already been fully written, in order to test whether it works correctly", "Only while a program is actually running, to control how fast it processes data", "Only by professional programmers, and only when they are using a single specific programming language"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Computational thinking is used before any code is written, to plan and simplify a solution to a problem."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:e5ebce22', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking an algorithm and algorithmic thinking are the same thing.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <strong>Algorithmic thinking</strong> is the thinking <em>process</em> of working out the steps needed. An <strong>algorithm</strong> is the <em>result</em> — the finished sequence of steps itself.</p>", "question": "What is the difference between an algorithm and algorithmic thinking?", "options": ["Algorithmic thinking is the process of working out the steps; an algorithm is the finished sequence of steps produced", "There is no difference — an algorithm and algorithmic thinking are simply two different names that always mean precisely the same single idea", "An algorithm is a computer, and algorithmic thinking is a type of computer program", "Algorithmic thinking is only used in maths lessons, and algorithms are only used in computing lessons"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Algorithmic thinking is the process of working out the steps; an algorithm is the result — the finished sequence of steps itself."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:misc:71580634', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing computational thinking techniques must always be used in one fixed order and never revisited.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> In practice the three techniques are used <strong>flexibly</strong> — a programmer might return to abstraction or decomposition again if a sub-problem turns out to be too complex, rather than moving through them only once.</p>", "question": "Must abstraction, decomposition and algorithmic thinking always be used in a strict, one-way order?", "options": ["No — a programmer can return to an earlier technique, such as decomposing a sub-problem further, if needed", "Yes, they must always be used in the exact same fixed order, with absolutely no exceptions ever allowed at all", "No, because only one of the three techniques is ever needed to solve any problem at all", "Yes, but only when the problem being solved involves numbers rather than any other kind of data"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The techniques are used flexibly — a programmer can revisit an earlier one (e.g. decomposing further) if a sub-problem is still too complex."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tips:4751a8d5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Naming the right technique — look for the cue words", "reading": "<p>\"Identify the technique used\" questions are answered by spotting <strong>cue words</strong> in the scenario, not by guessing.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Abstraction</strong> — look for words like <em>ignore, leave out, hide, simplify</em>, or \"only the detail that matters\".</li>\n<li><strong>Decomposition</strong> — look for words like <em>split, divide, break down</em>, or a problem described as several separate parts.</li>\n<li><strong>Algorithmic thinking</strong> — look for an <em>ordered list of steps</em>, or words like \"first, then, finally\".</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Always answer using the <strong>exact term</strong> the mark scheme expects — \"decomposition\", not \"breaking it into bits\" — and back it up with a short reason from the scenario.</p>", "question": "A scenario says an app designer ''decided the app did not need to record every user''s exact age, only whether they were under or over 18.'' Which cue tells you this is abstraction?", "options": ["The unnecessary detail (the exact age) has been simplified down to only what is needed", "The overall design task has been split into several separate, smaller sub-problems for different people to build", "The exact order of steps needed to check a user''s age has been written out in full", "The finished algorithm has been tested to make sure it works correctly every time"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Simplifying detail down to only what is needed (exact age → under/over 18) is the cue for abstraction, not decomposition, algorithmic thinking or testing."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tips:0ce7f4a3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Explaining a benefit — always link it back to the problem", "reading": "<p>\"State/explain one benefit of decomposition\" answers lose marks when they just repeat the definition. Structure your answer in <strong>two parts</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>1) Name the benefit — e.g. easier to test, easier to share between people, or a sub-problem can be reused.</li>\n<li>2) Explain <strong>why</strong> it helps, linked to the sub-problems being smaller and simpler than the whole problem.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> \"Decomposition makes a solution easier to test, because each small sub-problem can be checked on its own, rather than trying to test the whole complicated program all at once.\"</p>", "question": "Which answer best explains a benefit of decomposition, rather than just naming it?", "options": ["It is easier to test, because each small sub-problem can be checked separately rather than testing the whole program at once", "Testing", "It makes the entire problem completely disappear, meaning that no testing of any kind is ever required from anyone at all, under any circumstances", "Decomposition"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A full answer names the benefit AND explains why it happens (smaller sub-problems are easier to check individually) — a single word does not explain anything."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking:tips:6af4b12d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-1-1-computational-thinking', '2.1.1 Computational Thinking', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Answering a longer ''apply computational thinking'' scenario question", "reading": "<p>Longer questions describe a real problem and ask you to describe how computational thinking could be used to plan a solution. Structure your answer around the <strong>three techniques</strong>, one paragraph each:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Abstraction</strong> — say which details from the scenario would be kept, and which would be left out, and why.</li>\n<li><strong>Decomposition</strong> — say how the scenario''s problem could be split into named sub-problems.</li>\n<li><strong>Algorithmic thinking</strong> — say that the steps for one of those sub-problems would then be worked out in order.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use details from the <strong>scenario itself</strong> in each paragraph — a generic definition with no reference to the scenario will not gain full marks.</p>", "question": "A 6-mark question gives a scenario and asks how computational thinking could be applied to it. What is the best way to structure the answer?", "options": ["Cover each of abstraction, decomposition and algorithmic thinking in turn, applying each one to details from the scenario", "Write out only the plain dictionary definitions of the three separate terms, without referring to any specific detail from the scenario given in the question at all", "Focus entirely on writing the final program code needed to solve the scenario in a specific language", "Describe only decomposition in detail, since it is the single most important of the three techniques"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The strongest answers cover all three techniques and apply each one to the scenario''s own details, rather than giving generic definitions or code."}'::jsonb),
